<br>
There are 3 levels of call for help.<br>
<br>
0 - Unheard call) No matter what you do to one enemy, the other enemies will not respond to calls for help. This occurs when your level is much greater than the enemies that would normally respond to calls for help. <br>
<br>
1 - Soft call) An enemy is agrod, but is not having damage done to it via melee or spell at close range (for example, a shot of an arrow, a nuke from 150 units away,...), and the enemy's friend is within call for help range. Soft calls for help are only successful if the player or pet is under 10 levels above the level of the enemy.<br>
<br>
2 - Loud call) An enemy is engaged in melee combat or spell combat by a player from close range (melee range), and the enemy's friend is within call for help range.<br>
<br>
The &quot;unheard&quot; call for help seems to only happen with low level enemies (dervish cutthroats, blackburrow gnolls, etc). If you're 10 levels or more above an enemy's level, a soft call for help will not yield aid from more enemies. No amount of levels will prevent a loud call for help from being successful. Call for help ranges seem to be static per enemy. In other words, each type of enemy has a set value for the range that its call can be heard (your pet will not make the enemy increase its range no matter what).<br>
<br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
There are two levels of proximity agro as well. I am not sure on the level ranges, but the two levels only apply to some low level mobs (dervish cutthroats, enemies in paludal caverns, blackburrow gnolls).<br>
<br>
Level 1 - you are low in level) Every enemy will attack you when you are within their sight range. Sight ranges are variable with respect to your level. A level 60 can stand closer to a spite golem without agroing than a level 1 can stand.<br>
<br>
Level 2 - you are high in level) The enemy will not attack you no matter how much you let him see you.<br>
<br>
Level 2 is only apparent for low level creatures, as stated above. For the majority of NPCs, Level 1 proximity aggro ALWAYS applies.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
If everything here works the way I described it, then your pet's low level will only screw things up if you pull with your pet. The one rare case I can think of where you would be &quot;pulling&quot; with your pet is if you attack a wizard NPC, and you get nuked by the NPC - your pet would then Taunt, or cast a spell back at the NPC, and thus cause another &quot;small call for help&quot; by the wizard NPC. Because your pet is lower level than you, he may not be 10 levels above the enemy, and therefore the enemy's call for help would be successful. In a dungeon like Ssra where the enemies are all high level, your pet does not bring additional risk because *no one* is 10 levels higher than any NPC there.  <p><img src="http://www.lehigh.edu/~dsf3/EQ/rhionsligo.jpg" align="center"><br>
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=106710">My Character Profile</a>
